subSubSection.paragraph:
Monodelphis arlindoi

sp. nov.
shows the extension of the body fur onto the tail and the tonality of the body fur variable. Specimens from Cachoeira Porteira, Oriximiná (Pará, 
Brazil
) have a longer proportion of the tail covered by body hairs (one third or slightly more) than specimens from Porto Trombetas (also in Oriximiná), Faro (Pará, 
Brazil
), and Alenquer (Pará, 
Brazil
) (one third). Specimens from the latter three localities show the greyish base of the venter more evident than specimens from Cachoeira Porteira. Specimens from 
Potaro-Siparuni
(
Guyana
) have about one half of the tail length covered by body fur, and the venter more greyish than all other specimens examined. Specimens from Manaus and Itacoatiara (Amazonas, 
Brazil
) appear smaller than specimens from all other localities and exhibit underparts more yellowish, more extensive coverage of the tail by body fur (at least one half of the tail length, commonly more), and mid-dorsal fur with greyish tonality lighter than average in this species, whitish or yellowish at head’s crown. Specimens from these two municipalities also exhibit smaller skull, and zygomatic arches less expanded to laterals than average for this species.
